Pour @water{300%ml}(cold salted, double for 4p) into a #medium pot{} with a
tight-fitting #lid{}. Stir in the @jasmine rice{150%g} and bring to the boil.

Once boiling, lower the heat to medium and cover with the lid. Leave to cook for
~{12%minutes}, then remove the pot from the heat and leave to the side for
another ~{12%minutes} or until ready to serve (keep covered so the rice can
continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, mix the @sweet chilli sauce{2%sachets}, @soy sauce{1%sachet} and
@oil{1%tbsp}(double for 4p) in a #large bowl{}. Coat the @hake{250%g} in the
sauce and leave to marinate.

Place a #large pan{} over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Roughly chop the @coriander{5%g}(stalks and all). Trim the @pak choi{2%units}
then separate the leaves. Once pan is hot, fry the pak choi for ~{3-4%minutes},
turning as it starts to char. Season with @salt{to taste} and
@pepper{to taste}. Remove from the pan and set aside.

Return the pan to high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}. Once hot, add the
marinated hake (reserving the marinade in the #bowl{}).

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw fish. Fish is cooked when opaque in the middle.

Fry on one side until golden, ~{2-3%minutes}. Turn over and cook for
~{2-3%minutes} on the other side. When 1 min of cooking time remains, add the
marinade and coat the hake in it. Allow the sauce to reduce slightly.

Dish up the fragrant rice and charred pak choi. Top with the charred hake and
drizzle over any marinade that remains in the pan. Garnish with the chopped
coriander.